The course spans four semesters. The first semester introduces applied behavioral science as a curriculum, as a profession, and as a thesis topic. The second semester involves completing a behavioural problem-solving cycle. In the third and fourth semesters, the course will take less time and offers support for writing the thesis and opportunities to design your own coursework.Objectives/eesmärkid:  This course aids the development of competences in the application of behavioural science, including behavioral problem analysis, mapping of interventions, and measuring their impact. It integrates knowledge and skills acquired in other courses as well as scaffolds work on the Master thesis.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  A student who has successfully defended their master's thesis can:  identify behaviours that can be influenced to achieve selected broader objectives finds and conducts research to better understand the behaviour of selected target groups constructs a model describing the main causes of the selected behaviour to be influenced develops techniques to influence the selected behaviour ethically and effectively in the desired direction designs and, if possible, conducts an effectiveness study of the selected intervention
